    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1879-02-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1879-02-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="211"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d211">
                <head>No. 190.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Evarts</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Welsh</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1879-02-18">
                            <hi rend="italic">February</hi> 18, 1879</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 233.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: At a recent convocation of boards of railroad
                    commissioners held at Columbus Ohio, a committee was appointed to examine and
                    report <pb facs="0510" n="414" xml:id="pg_414"/> upon the methods of taxation as
                    respects railroads and railroad securities now in use in the various States in
                    the Union, as well as in foreign countries.</p>
                <p>Mr. Charles F. Adams, jr., of Boston, the chairman of that committee, has
                    requested the co-operation of this Department with a view to obtain the
                    information desired from abroad. As the object in view is deemed to be one of
                    national interest, I have to request you to obtain and transmit to the
                    Department, at your earliest convenience, such statements in detail as are
                    obtainable, and as may be necessay for a correct understanding of the systems of
                    railroad taxation in use in Great Britain. The information should especially
                    cover the following points, namely: <list>
                        <label>1st.</label>
                        <item>On what general recognized principle, if any, is the railroad taxation
                            of Great Britain based”?</item>
                        <label>2d.</label>
                        <item>In how far are the railroad companies taxed as holders of
                            realty?</item>
                        <label>3d.</label>
                        <item>In how far as holders of personalty?</item>
                        <label>4th.</label>
                        <item>In how far are they subject to a franchise tax?</item>
                        <label>5th.</label>
                        <item>In how far is their stock taxed as personalty to its owner?</item>
                        <label>6th.</label>
                        <item>What taxes are levied on the receipts of the companies, whether net or
                            gross?</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WM. M. EVARTS.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Note.</hi>—A similar instruction pent to the minister
                        to Austria-Hungary, Belgium, France, Germany, Italy, Russia, and
                        Switzerland.</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
